  "title": "French Passé Composé: Past Participles",
  "description": "Past participle endings, irregular participles, avoir/être, and agreement basics",
  "questionCount": 50,
  "crashCourse": {
    "title": "Passé composé and past participles",
    "subtitle": "The core formula is present-tense auxiliary + past participle.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "title": "Formula",
        "content": "Use avoir or être in the present + the past participle.",
        "tip": "j’ai parlé, elle est partie, nous avons fini."
      },
      {
        "title": "Regular participles",
        "content": "-er → -é, regular -ir → -i, many -re verbs → -u.",
        "tip": "parler → parlé; finir → fini; vendre → vendu."
      },
      {
        "title": "Irregular participles",
        "content": "Common forms must be memorized.",
        "tip": "avoir → eu, être → été, faire → fait, voir → vu, prendre → pris, mettre → mis, écrire → écrit, dire → dit."
      },
      {
        "title": "Avoir vs être",
        "content": "Most verbs use avoir. Movement/change-of-state verbs and all pronominal verbs use être.",
        "tip": "je suis allé, elle est née, nous nous sommes levés."
      },
      {
        "title": "Agreement basics",
        "content": "With être, the participle agrees with the subject. With avoir, it usually does not agree unless a direct object comes before.",
        "tip": "elle est allée; ils sont partis; les lettres que j’ai écrites."
      }
    ]
  },
